Michael Hillegas. April 22, 1729, to September 29, 1804. He was, as the records state, the *first* [Treasurer of the United States](/Treasurer_of_the_United_States). A designation that carries weight, I suppose, if you’re into that sort of thing.

#### Biography

Born in [Philadelphia](/Philadelphia), Pennsylvania, Hillegas was the offspring of Margaret Schiebenstock and George Michael Hillegass. His father, an immigrant from [Germany](/Germany), was a merchant of some means, dealing in iron and sugar. This established background, this comfortable footing, afforded young Michael the luxury of dabbling in public affairs. He married Henrietta Boude on May 10, 1753, at Christ Church in Philadelphia – a rather quaint detail, isn't it? They managed to produce a rather significant number of children.

Hillegas carved out a presence in the [Pennsylvania Provincial Assembly](/Pennsylvania_Provincial_Assembly) for a decade, from 1765 to 1775. He even served as [treasurer](/Treasurer) for the [Committee of Safety](/Committee_of_Safety_(American_Revolution)) under the rather more famous [Benjamin Franklin](/Benjamin_Franklin) in 1774. A footnote, perhaps, but a significant one.

Then came July 29, 1775. The [Continental Congress](/Continental_Congress), in its infinite wisdom, decided to split the role of Treasurer of the United Colonies between Hillegas and [George Clymer](/George_Clymer). It’s a curious footnote that Hillegas was involved in editing the [Declaration of Independence](/United_States_Declaration_of_Independence), yet it was Clymer’s signature that graced the final document. A matter of process, or perhaps, a subtle erasure.

After Clymer bowed out on August 6, 1776, Hillegas was left holding the entire, rather precarious, bag. He managed the nation's coffers throughout the brutal slog of the [American Revolution](/American_Revolution), even dipping into his own considerable fortune to keep the wheels turning. A patriotic gesture, or a pragmatic investment? His son, Samuel, was authorized to sign the dubious "Continentals" currency, a testament to the family’s entanglement with the nation's nascent finances. Hillegas also took on duties as a quartermaster and served on various commissions. The country officially became the [United States of America](/United_States) on September 9, 1776, but the title of Treasurer didn't catch up until March 1778. The whole structure shifted when [Alexander Hamilton](/Alexander_Hamilton) took the helm as the first [Secretary of the Treasury](/United_States_Secretary_of_the_Treasury) on September 11, 1789. On that same day, Hillegas submitted his resignation, making way for [Samuel Meredith](/Samuel_Meredith_(American_politician)) to step in. A clean handover, one presumes.

He was also an early member of the [American Philosophical Society](/American_Philosophical_Society), alongside Franklin. A club for the intellectually inclined, I suppose. He died in Philadelphia, finding his final resting place not far from Franklin himself, in [Christ Church Burial Ground](/Christ_Church_Burial_Ground). It wasn't until the late 19th century that his descendants decided his portrait deserved a place on the ten-dollar [gold certificate](/Gold_certificate_(United_States)) issued in 1907 and 1922. A posthumous recognition, a quiet echo in the annals of currency.

